<h2>A Brief Word on the Filioque</h2>

<p>Eastern and Western Christians disagree about the Holy Spirit. The disagreement centers on a single Latin word: <em>filioque</em>, "and the Son." The original Nicene Creed (381 AD) states that the Holy Spirit "proceeds from the Father." At some point in the early medieval West, the words "and the Son" were added, so that the Spirit "proceeds from the Father <em>and the Son</em>."</p>

<p>For Eastern Christians, this addition is problematic, both because it was made without the consent of an ecumenical council and because it seems to alter the relationship among the Persons of the Trinity. The East maintains that the Father alone is the Source (<em>monarchia</em>) of both the Son and the Spirit, and that the filioque risks subordinating the Spirit to the Son.</p>

<p>This is a genuine theological difference, and it has contributed to centuries of division. But many theologians on both sides, including recent popes and patriarchs, have worked toward a shared understanding. The Eastern position is not that the Son has <em>no</em> role in the Spirit's mission, but that the language of "procession" must be used carefully. A conversation still in progress, better served by patience than by polemic.</p>

<p>St. Basil's <em>On the Holy Spirit</em> is the place to start for anyone wanting the Eastern position stated with precision and force.</p>

<h2>The <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#trisagion">Trisagion</a> and the Life of the Spirit</h2>

<p>Three times in the Divine Liturgy, the congregation sings the <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#trisagion">Trisagion</a>: "Holy God, Holy Mighty, Holy Immortal, have mercy on us." One of the oldest hymns in the Christian tradition, a prayer addressed to the Trinity, three times holy, echoing the song of the seraphim in Isaiah's vision of heaven.</p>

<p>The repetition is deliberate. Eastern worship is not afraid of repetition, because the Spirit works through repetition the way water works through stone. Slowly, patiently, shaping the soul by gradual pressure rather than dramatic force. The <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#trisagion">Trisagion</a> is said three times. The Lord's Prayer is preceded by silence. The Jesus Prayer is repeated thousands of times. In each case, the human being is creating space, and the Spirit is filling it.</p>

<p>The next step looks at the community that the Spirit brought into existence on Pentecost: the Church itself, its structure, its self-understanding, and why Eastern Christians believe that the local parish gathered around its bishop is the Church in its fullness.</p>

<Layer2Panel label="Christ Our Pascha on the Holy Spirit">
  <p><em>Christ Our Pascha</em> §§ 101–125 presents the Holy Spirit as "the Lord and Giver of Life" who proceeds from the Father, is worshipped and glorified together with the Father and the Son, and is active in every aspect of the Church's life. The catechism emphasizes the Spirit's role in the sacraments: it is the Spirit who consecrates the Eucharistic gifts (§114), seals the newly baptized in chrismation (§110), and empowers every Christian for mission and holiness.</p>
</Layer2Panel>

